    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-8998' data-commentid="8998" data-postid="1326" data-belowelement="comment-8998" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Molly" aria-label='Reply to Molly'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-8999" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://52churches.garriber.org" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Jen</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/02/consider-it/#comment-8999"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2008-07-25T15:21:00-04:00">Friday, July 25, 2008 at 3:21 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I disagree that the single serving size applesauces are necessarily a waste.  </></>Like you, I don&#39;t eat applesauce on its own (er&#8211;I&#39;m assuming that&#39;s why yours goes bad in the fridge&#8211;it&#39;s the reason mine does), so large containers go to waste in the intervening time between making things that involve applesauce.</></>If, in an effort to have less packaging, you buy, say, a 16 oz. jar for the &lt;1 cup of applesauce you need and it goes bad, at then end of 6 such recipes and an interval of 2 years, you&#39;ll have 6 jars, 6 lids, and over 5 pounds of applesauce that went bad.  </>In the same interval, you could have 6 pieces of foil (the &#8220;lid&#8221; of those cups), 1 tag board holder, 6 small #7 plastic cups, and no applesauce.</></>Of course, now #7 plastic is hideously bad for you . . . you can&#39;t win unless you boil your own apple: 1 compostable core and skin, 1 super sticky sticker, small energy output for cooking and blending.</></>ðŸ™‚</></>&#8211;Jen</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-8999' data-commentid="8999" data-postid="1326" data-belowelement="comment-8999" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Jen" aria-label='Reply to Jen'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-9000" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/14743154513490908895" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Melody</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/02/consider-it/#comment-9000"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2008-08-04T22:25:00-04:00">Monday, August 4, 2008 at 10:25 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I am going to try this, but need to substitute the nuts with nut free products like soy nuts.  Do you know anything about cooking with soy nuts?  I&#8217;ve been looking for recipes for granola and granola bars for my family and especially 3 year old to enjoy (allergy to peanuts/tree nuts).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-9000' data-commentid="9000" data-postid="1326" data-belowelement="comment-9000" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Melody" aria-label='Reply to Melody'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-9001" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
